265
00:19:58,840 --> 00:20:00,679
Are you two an item?

266
00:20:00,679 --> 00:20:03,319
A snog in the ladies'
at the Christmas party.

267
00:20:03,319 --> 00:20:07,279
But I can't talk about it here cos
of Craig's, you know...position.

268
00:20:07,279 --> 00:20:09,320
Do you want to meet lunchtime
for a chat?

269
00:20:10,999 --> 00:20:13,840
OK. Where does Gary sit?

270
00:20:13,840 --> 00:20:17,239
Number 50. OK, thank you. Thanks.

271
00:20:25,720 --> 00:20:27,679
MOBILE RINGS

272
00:20:28,759 --> 00:20:32,440
Owen. 'Gwen, Jack wants to know
where you are.' Yeah, sorry.

273
00:20:32,440 --> 00:20:37,039
I had a few things to sort out.
I'll be back later.
'Yeah, well, make it quick.'

274
00:20:41,960 --> 00:20:46,080
Well, one day Eugene came in,
very low. Why? Why was he low?

275
00:20:46,080 --> 00:20:48,439
He wouldn't talk about it.

276
00:20:48,439 --> 00:20:51,520
Anyway, I was fed up too
because Craig had...

277
00:20:51,520 --> 00:20:56,320
Well, anyway, I said,
I'd love to get away from it all
and go to Australia.

278
00:20:56,320 --> 00:21:00,640
Eugene suddenly got very excited.
He said, "Yes! You've got to go."

279
00:21:00,640 --> 00:21:03,240
I said,
"But I haven't got the money,"

280
00:21:03,240 --> 00:21:05,679
and he said he'd get it for me.

281
00:21:05,679 --> 00:21:09,839
So he was going to pay for a ticket
for you to go to Australia with him?
Was he in love with you?

282
00:21:09,839 --> 00:21:12,600
Oh, no! He loved someone
he said was unattainable.

283
00:21:15,239 --> 00:21:19,039
He was just trying to look after me.
He said,

284
00:21:19,039 --> 00:21:25,279
"Don't stay here
and waste your life waiting for
something that may never happen."

285
00:21:25,279 --> 00:21:27,679
Where was he going to get
the money from? Exactly.

286
00:21:27,679 --> 00:21:29,839
You said, "You haven't bought socks
in six years."

287
00:21:29,839 --> 00:21:33,280
I said, "You haven't even had
a new pair of socks in six years."

288
00:21:33,280 --> 00:21:37,959
He stood up, and he said...
MOBILE RINGS
That's your phone.

289
00:21:37,959 --> 00:21:41,199
Yeah, he said...? He said,

290
00:21:41,199 --> 00:21:43,239
"I'm going to sell it."

291
00:21:43,239 --> 00:21:45,919
I said, "What?"

292
00:21:45,919 --> 00:21:51,199
He said, "My alien artefact." So...?
So...? So he brought it in to work.

293
00:21:57,400 --> 00:22:03,199
It's a plastic eye!
It's an alien body part,
and I'm going to sell it on eBay.

294
00:22:03,199 --> 00:22:07,999
Eugene, it's very nice of you,
but I don't think that's going
to get me the bus into town,

295
00:22:07,999 --> 00:22:10,000
let alone a flight to Sydney.

296
00:22:12,640 --> 00:22:18,040
Some people laughed.
But he went ahead,
and of course, it just sat there.

297
00:22:18,040 --> 00:22:21,240
She said maybe a photo,
a bit more of a description...

298
00:22:21,240 --> 00:22:24,000
Then, out of the blue - £2.50.

299
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:26,239
A kid from Birmingham.

300
00:22:26,239 --> 00:22:30,120
And then...
Eugene, you got a couple more bids.

301
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:32,959
Bloody hell! 75 quid!

302
00:22:32,959 --> 00:22:35,400
That was just the beginning.

303
00:22:35,400 --> 00:22:38,680
200... 300...

304
00:22:38,680 --> 00:22:42,720
1,000... They just kept on going up.

305
00:22:42,720 --> 00:22:45,799
£3,000! For a spare body part.

306
00:22:45,799 --> 00:22:50,400
Pete said you can get
a bathroom suite with a celebrity
appearance for less than that!

307
00:22:50,400 --> 00:22:52,200
Then one day, it just...

308
00:22:52,200 --> 00:22:53,999
jumped.

309
00:22:57,240 --> 00:22:59,439
Oh, my God, Eugene, you're rich!

310
00:23:03,240 --> 00:23:06,319
£15,005.50.

311
00:23:06,319 --> 00:23:08,520
Who bought it? Who bought it?

312
00:23:08,520 --> 00:23:11,880
I've no idea. Is it all my fault?

313
00:23:11,880 --> 00:23:17,080
Of course it's not!
MOBILE RINGS
I'm sorry.

314
00:23:17,080 --> 00:23:19,639
Hello? 'Hi, it's Eugene's mum.'

315
00:23:19,639 --> 00:23:24,960
Mrs Jones? 'There's something
I think you should see.'
OK. I'll come over.

316
00:23:24,960 --> 00:23:28,559
That was Eugene's mum.
Sorry, I'm going to have to go.

317
00:23:28,559 --> 00:23:30,040
I'm sorry.

318
00:23:37,160 --> 00:23:42,360
MAN: There he is...my son at the
Interschool Maths Final. Big moment.

319
00:23:42,360 --> 00:23:45,400
Youngest contestant in Wales.

320
00:23:45,400 --> 00:23:50,560
So, it's down to the wire, the
last question will settle the final.

321
00:23:50,560 --> 00:23:54,920
What curve is represented by
y-squared = 4ax?

322
00:23:57,600 --> 00:24:02,239
Come on. You got a brain the
size of Cardiff Arms Park!
What's the friggin' problem?!

323
00:24:02,239 --> 00:24:06,959
What curve is represented by
y-squared = 4ax? Don't do this.

324
00:24:06,959 --> 00:24:09,199
Don't let me down, boy.

325
00:24:09,199 --> 00:24:11,359
No?

326
00:24:11,359 --> 00:24:14,239
DING!
Time's up. No additional points.

327
00:24:14,239 --> 00:24:16,800
The final scores are...

328
00:24:16,800 --> 00:24:21,280
I don't understand. Someone gave him
the eye as a consolation prize?

329
00:24:21,280 --> 00:24:25,479
Yeah, it was that Mr Garrett,
the science teacher.

330
00:24:25,479 --> 00:24:27,040
A plastic eye!

331
00:24:27,040 --> 00:24:29,560
As a consolation prize!

332
00:24:29,560 --> 00:24:33,960
Still, Eugene treasured it.
That was the night Dad walked out.
Went away.

333
00:24:33,960 --> 00:24:37,600
You can stop now, Mum.
What do you mean? He's dead.

334
00:24:37,600 --> 00:24:43,080
He may have been able to square
the root of the square root, but he
couldn't cross the road! Terry!

335
00:24:43,080 --> 00:24:47,200
He sold the eye online.

336
00:24:47,200 --> 00:24:49,399
So something must have happened.

337
00:24:49,399 --> 00:24:55,360
Dad left when he found out Eugene
was a failure. That's what Eugene
said. None of that's true.

338
00:24:55,360 --> 00:24:58,000
He went cos of his job.

339
00:24:58,000 --> 00:24:59,880
He has a very important job.

340
00:24:59,880 --> 00:25:03,759
Does Mr Jones know about Eugene?

341
00:25:03,759 --> 00:25:07,680
Well, you see, he works for
a big corporation

342
00:25:07,680 --> 00:25:13,920
in America. Stop giving us that shit!
He's not Superman, Mum! He works at
a garage on Filey Road.

343
00:25:13,920 --> 00:25:17,719
Eugene found him about two weeks
ago. He found him on the internet.

344
00:25:17,719 --> 00:25:19,719
He's a cashier. Works nights.

345
00:25:27,160 --> 00:25:30,079
Oh, God, now I remember
why I sold the eye.

346
00:25:34,999 --> 00:25:37,959
Life can be such a let down,
can't it?

347
00:25:37,959 --> 00:25:42,120
All those years I'd believed
my dad had gone to America
because I was a failure.

348
00:25:42,120 --> 00:25:48,600
And here he was, all along,
doing his important secret
work in Filey Road, Cardiff.

349
00:25:48,600 --> 00:25:52,960
When I found him,
I couldn't even bear to say hello.

350
00:25:52,960 --> 00:25:56,360
I'd spent my life believing
in stupid stories, fantasies.

351
00:25:56,360 --> 00:25:59,040
I've wasted my life.

352
00:25:59,040 --> 00:26:02,680
Once I'd seen him there, everything
I'd dreamed about was like rubbish,

353
00:26:02,680 --> 00:26:07,759
just a crock of shit,
including the eye.

354
00:26:07,759 --> 00:26:10,200
So why not sell it?

355
00:26:10,200 --> 00:26:14,159
Along with the woodworm
treatment and loft insulation,

356
00:26:14,159 --> 00:26:17,679
and all the other crap floating
round the world.

357
00:26:17,679 --> 00:26:20,079
Linda was welcome to the money.

358
00:26:20,079 --> 00:26:22,119
No! No! NO! Don't, Gwen!

359
00:26:27,480 --> 00:26:29,319
I don't want anything to do with him.

360
00:26:34,399 --> 00:26:36,799
I'm sorry.

361
00:26:36,799 --> 00:26:38,239
It's OK.

362
00:26:58,080 --> 00:27:00,439
You turned your phone off.

363
00:27:02,319 --> 00:27:04,639
It was Eugene.

364
00:27:04,639 --> 00:27:07,999
He didn't understand
why his father left.

365
00:27:07,999 --> 00:27:10,360
He just needs a bit of help.

366
00:27:10,360 --> 00:27:13,359
To do what? He's dead!
Yes, Jack, I know he's dead, but...

367
00:27:13,359 --> 00:27:15,840
This is not sounding good, Gwen.

368
00:27:15,840 --> 00:27:18,559
I've got work to do. OK.

369
00:27:18,559 --> 00:27:20,679
Eh? No. You can't just stop.

370
00:27:20,679 --> 00:27:24,160
I mean, what about the £15,000?
Gwen? Gwen! OK. Listen to this.

371
00:27:24,160 --> 00:27:28,519
Eugene had an alien eye in his
collection. He sold it online.

372
00:27:28,519 --> 00:27:30,959
What, like a sixth eye?

373
00:27:30,959 --> 00:27:33,439
A Dogon sixth eye?

374
00:27:33,439 --> 00:27:35,959
Maybe.

375
00:27:35,959 --> 00:27:38,799
It's possible.
There was a trade in them.

376
00:27:38,799 --> 00:27:42,360
Who's got it? I don't know, but
I've nearly tracked it down.

377
00:27:42,360 --> 00:27:45,800
What exactly is a sixth eye?
I mean, exactly?

378
00:27:45,800 --> 00:27:49,039
It's one in the back. Let's you
see behind you, where you've been.

379
00:27:49,039 --> 00:27:52,239
Kind of puts things in perspective.

380
00:27:52,239 --> 00:27:55,800
It's useful,
fun, slightly terrifying,
that's why they were in demand.

381
00:27:55,800 --> 00:27:58,959
See? See? I told you.
I can get it for you.

382
00:27:58,959 --> 00:28:01,240
My alien...

383
00:28:01,240 --> 00:28:02,760
See? See?

384
00:28:02,760 --> 00:28:05,160
OK, you've got the weekend.

385
00:28:05,160 --> 00:28:08,440
But keep your phone on.

386
00:28:08,440 --> 00:28:10,320
God, you are brilliant.

387
00:28:10,320 --> 00:28:12,960
And I'm brilliant too.

388
00:28:12,960 --> 00:28:18,759
Oh, yeah, of course,
Gary and me were going to go to
that talk in Aberystwyth.

389
00:28:18,759 --> 00:28:23,160
Black holes and anti-matter were
pretty important to me and Gary, but

390
00:28:23,160 --> 00:28:26,200
if I'm going to spend a night by the
sea, I know who I'd rather be with.

391
00:28:27,759 --> 00:28:29,799
I'd trust you with my life

392
00:28:29,799 --> 00:28:32,719
if, you know, I still had one.

393
00:29:08,119 --> 00:29:09,079
Gary?

394
00:29:21,199 --> 00:29:22,760
I'm not proud of what I've done.

395
00:29:25,320 --> 00:29:31,680
You hiked the bid? I created
three or four online aliases,
and used them to inflate the price.

396
00:29:31,680 --> 00:29:33,559
But why?

397
00:29:33,559 --> 00:29:37,759
At first, just to cheer him up.
He was miserable.

398
00:29:37,759 --> 00:29:39,559
But then the bidding
took off and we got...

399
00:29:39,559 --> 00:29:43,519
I mean, I was involved at first.

400
00:29:43,519 --> 00:29:46,920
I was just helping Eugene make money,
and then one morning...

401
00:29:48,480 --> 00:29:49,959
Gary!

402
00:29:52,279 --> 00:29:54,400
Gary, I think it's him.

403
00:29:54,400 --> 00:29:56,479
Who? The alien.

404
00:29:56,479 --> 00:29:58,119
My alien.

405
00:29:58,119 --> 00:30:01,640
I think he's come back to
claim what's rightfully his.

406
00:30:01,640 --> 00:30:06,159
Gary, I'd stopped believing in him.
I mean, I thought I was just
a total sucker but...

407
00:30:06,159 --> 00:30:08,920
Who else would be bidding this
kind of money for a prosthetic eye?

408
00:30:10,479 --> 00:30:12,360
